Former president Jacob Zuma's lawyer says his client will appeal a court ruling that he stand trial on corruption charges. Courtesy #DStv403 PIETERMARITZBURG - Former president Jacob Zuma is taking his fight to not pay legal costs to the Supreme Court of Appeal. The court is set to hear his challenge of the ten million rand personal costs order in his failed state-capture report litigation after the High Court in Pretoria dismissed his application for leave to appeal. READ: Zuma says his health a priority Zuma sought to have the personal costs order scrapped. The court will also hear arguments whether he was reckless to approach the court to review the remedial action contained in former Public Protector Thuli Madonsela's State Capture Report.